From: Petr Wozniak <petr.wozniak@gmail.com>
Date: Fri, 26 Jun 2026 16:00:00 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 6.6] net: pcs: mtk-lynxi: don't report link up with
 unresolved speed in link_poll

The link_poll mechanism (commit 7dfffc16b710 "net: pcs: mtk-lynxi: add
link_poll mechanism") caches the link state produced by
mtk_pcs_lynxi_update_state().  In the non-autoneg path the speed is
decoded from the SGMII_SPEED_MASK field of SGMSYS_SGMII_MODE.  During
a 10GBASE-R -> 1000BASE-X (XGDM->GDM) transition this field briefly
reads a reserved value, so the switch leaves state->speed unresolved
while state->link has already been set from BMSR_LSTATUS.

get_state then reports "Link is Up - Unsupported/Half", phylink brings
the MAC up with no valid speed configured, and on MediaTek GMAC the
Rx FSM wedges ("GMAC Rx hang", recoverable only by reboot).  Observed
on BPI-R4 Pro 8X with a copper (RTL8261BE) SFP module, reproducible
on a warm reboot with a 1G link partner.

Don't report the link as up while the speed is not a valid value; keep
it down so phylink re-polls until the speed resolves.  This is confined
to the link-up cached-state path and does not affect the link-down
recovery that link_poll provides.

Note: This patch targets the Linux 6.6 kernel with padavanonly's
existing PCS patches (999-2601 through 999-2608) already applied.
It requires mtk_pcs_lynxi_update_state() to exist — this function
was introduced in Linux 6.7+ via the link_poll backport.  If the
function is absent, this patch will fail to apply and should be
skipped.

Signed-off-by: Petr Wozniak <petr.wozniak@gmail.com>
---
 drivers/net/pcs/pcs-mtk-lynxi.c | 11 +++++++++++
 1 file changed, 11 insertions(+)

--- a/drivers/net/pcs/pcs-mtk-lynxi.c
+++ b/drivers/net/pcs/pcs-mtk-lynxi.c
@@ -158,6 +158,17 @@
 			state->duplex = DUPLEX_FULL;
 	}
 
+	/* Never report link-up with an unresolved/invalid speed: during a
+	 * mode change (e.g. 10GBASE-R -> 1000BASE-X) the SGMII speed field can
+	 * read back a reserved value, surfacing as "Link is Up - Unsupported"
+	 * and wedging the MAC Rx FSM.  Hold the link down so phylink re-polls
+	 * until the speed resolves to a valid value.
+	 */
+	if (state->link && state->speed != SPEED_10 &&
+	    state->speed != SPEED_100 && state->speed != SPEED_1000 &&
+	    state->speed != SPEED_2500)
+		state->link = false;
+
 	state->interface = mpcs->interface;
 
 	mutex_unlock(&mpcs->regmap_lock);
-- 
2.45.0
